The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences and dislikes (from my self-introduction):
- Prefer cohesive, artist‑driven, well‑sequenced studio albums with musical continuity that reward focused, repeat listening.
- Favor British/European releases and consistent mastering/pacing across a single disc.
- Like polished, CD‑level production that is atmospheric but detailed, with clear mixes and separation that reveal studio detail.
- Enjoy Classic Rock/AOR sensibilities: keyboards/piano/synth textures, strong melodic hooks, emotive ballads, tasteful horn/sax when present, concise arrangements, expressive vocals, and punchy (but not overdriven) rhythms.
- Dislike unevenly mastered compilations, mixes that bury midrange or vocals, dense multi‑tracked guitar stacking, excessive reverb, and long, guitar‑solo‑heavy tracks lacking textural variety.
Evaluation of the two candidates against those points:
- Peachtree Road:
  - Matches the cohesion and sequencing preference: described as a cohesive, carefully sequenced, single‑disc album with consistent pacing—exactly the sort of “album‑minded” listening I favor.
  - Matches British/artist‑driven angle (Elton John–style, piano‑led, late‑career artist focus).
  - Production aligns with my taste: polished CD‑level production, subtle arrangements, clear mixes and liner notes that reward full‑disc listening; this speaks to consistent mastering and detailed, intimate production rather than dense clutter.
  - Musical character (intimate, introspective, emotive ballads, restrained tempos, subtle arrangements) fits my preference for emotive songs, concise arrangements and expressive vocals, and avoids the heavy guitar stacking and long solo vehicles I dislike.
- New Wave/alternative record:
  - Satisfies many technical preferences: studio‑forward, layered synth textures, clear instrument separation, punchy rhythms, memorable singles, tasteful horn lines and concise arrangements—these are things I like (keyboards/synth, punch, clear mixes).
  - However, it explicitly mentions stylistic variety. While variety can be good, it works against my stated preference for musical continuity and a cohesive, well‑sequenced single‑mood album experience. “Stylistic variety” risks an uneven listening arc or less of the artist‑driven unity I prize.
  - The New Wave record’s strengths (memorable singles, textural richness) could make it more of a collection of standouts rather than the tightly unified, album‑minded record I said I now favor.
Reasoned choice:
I select Peachtree Road because it best aligns with the most central and repeatedly stated parts of my taste: a cohesive, artist‑driven, well‑sequenced studio album with consistent mastering and clear, intimate production that rewards full‑disc listening. Its piano‑led, emotive, subtly arranged songs match my preference for expressive vocals, emotive balladry and concise arrangements, and the single‑disc, consistent pacing avoids the unevenness and loss of continuity I dislike.
I reject the New Wave/alternative candidate not because it fails technically (it actually ticks many boxes: synth textures, clear separation, punchy rhythms and tasteful horns), but because its touted “stylistic variety” and emphasis on singles introduces a risk of a less cohesive, less artist‑driven album experience. Given I now prioritize albums that hang together as a unified statement and reward focused repeat plays, Peachtree Road is the better fit.

